\title{Spatio-Temporal Sequential Framework for Early Warning Signals of Bus Bunching in Transit Digital Twin Architectures}

\author{Carlos Stiven Mora Hoyos, Juan Felipe Rodríguez Galindo
\thanks{Manuscript received April 9, 2026; revised April 09, 2026. This work was supported by the pp-pipe-dt research initiative.}
\thanks{The authors are with the Department of Engineering (Bogotá, Colombia). Corresponding author: csmorah@udistrital.edu.co, juafrodriguezg@udistrital.edu.co}}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
	Bus bunching is a stochastic operational anomaly that severely impacts the reliability of high-frequency public transit corridors. While the integration of General Transit Feed Specification Realtime (GTFS-RT) data into Digital Twin (DT) architectures has gained traction, existing predictive models often suffer from high false-positive rates due to urban signal noise or fail to provide sufficient lead time for operational intervention. This paper proposes an empirical algorithmic framework for Early Warning Signals (EWS) focused on computational efficiency and sequential validation. Utilizing a dataset of approximately 1 million raw Automatic Vehicle Location (AVL) records from San Francisco Muni (February 2026)---strictly deduplicated to 205,584 valid observations to eliminate spatial data leakage---we demonstrate that a multi-stop sequential window ($n-3$) effectively filters transient noise. Our results show that a balanced Logistic Regression model, optimized via F1-score maximization and L2 regularization, achieves a precision of 0.95 (95\% CI: [0.93, 0.97]) and a corrected F1-score of 0.8234 (95\% CI: [0.80, 0.84]) for state transitions (nominal to bunching). We identify the rate of headway collapse ($\Delta H_{n-1}$) as the primary precursor signal ($w \approx -0.036$). Furthermore, we report an inference latency of \SI{0.00042}{\ms} per record utilizing an in-process analytical database (DuckDB), enabling regional-scale monitoring in real-time. This study provides the mathematical foundation and performance benchmarks for proactive transit management in mixed-traffic environments and lays the groundwork for control strategies in Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) systems.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
	Bus bunching, Digital Twins, Early warning signals, GTFS Realtime, Machine learning, Public transit, Spatio-temporal analysis, Edge Computing.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
\IEEEPARstart{T}{he} reliability of public transportation systems is a cornerstone of urban sustainability and economic efficiency. However, high-frequency transit lines are inherently unstable due to the ``bus bunching'' phenomenon, where small initial delays are amplified by increased passenger demand at subsequent stops, leading to vehicles clustering in convoys \cite{1,2}. This positive feedback loop causes a severe degradation of service quality, characterized by excessive passenger waiting times, uneven vehicle passenger loads, and a generalized loss of trust in the transit network's reliability \cite{3}. Traditional management strategies, primarily based on static General Transit Feed Specification (GTFS) schedules, are reactive and unable to detect these anomalies before they become systemic operational failures \cite{4}.

The recent paradigm shift towards Digital Twin (DT) architectures in transportation engineering offers a robust framework for real-time monitoring and proactive control \cite{5,6}. A transit DT requires a high-fidelity, real-time representation of the physical fleet, capable of ingesting massive streams of GTFS Realtime (GTFS-RT) Automatic Vehicle Location (AVL) data and executing predictive algorithms to mitigate bunching events \cite{7}. Despite the theoretical potential of DTs, the practical implementation of Early Warning Signals (EWS) remains challenging. Existing predictive frameworks suffer from two critical limitations: high False Positive Rates (FPR) due to the high variance of urban traffic signals (e.g., traffic lights, double parking), and the computational overhead required for large-scale fleet processing, which impedes true real-time responsiveness \cite{8,9}.

This paper addresses these gaps by presenting an empirical, algorithmically efficient proposal tailored for transit DT environments. By shifting from descriptive statistics and single-stop thresholding to a sequential spatio-temporal analysis, we identify the specific mathematical signatures that precede service collapse.

Our contribution is structured as follows:
\begin{itemize}
	\item We propose a multi-stop windowing framework ($n-3$) that acts as a low-pass filter for exogenous urban noise, drastically reducing the alarm fatigue common in transit control centers.
	\item We formulate an optimized, L2-regularized classifier for state transition prediction that completely eliminates persistence bias (target leakage), ensuring that the EWS detects genuine systemic transitions from a nominal state to a bunched state.
	\item We incorporate a conformal prediction layer to attach calibrated uncertainty sets to each alert, promoting risk-aware intervention policies rather than threshold-only triggering.
	\item We provide a rigorous computational benchmark of the ingestion and inference pipeline utilizing an embedded analytical database architecture (DuckDB), proving the viability of the system for Edge-Cloud DT deployments with sub-millisecond latencies.
	\item We embrace open science by making our entire data pipeline and modeling code open-source for full reproducibility.
\end{itemize}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section II reviews the state of the art. Section III details the system architecture and mathematical formulation, including uncertainty quantification through conformal prediction. Section IV outlines the experimental setup. Section V presents the results, including spatial cross-validation and feature importance. Section VI discusses the operational implications and the future integration with Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) control strategies, followed by concluding remarks in Section VII.

\section{Related Work}

To construct a robust EWS framework, this study synthesizes literature across four distinct domains: headway dynamics, data ingestion architectures, predictive modeling for imbalanced data, and Digital Twin frameworks.

\subsection{Headway Dynamics and Bus Bunching Physics}
The instability of high-frequency transit lines was mathematically formalized by Daganzo \cite{1}, who demonstrated that headway variance grows exponentially without active control. Bartholdi and Eisenstein \cite{2} further expanded on this by proposing self-coordinating, headway-based control strategies that abandon static schedules in favor of dynamic equalization. These seminal works establish that the relative distance between consecutive buses (headway) is a far superior metric for system stability than schedule adherence (delay). Recent studies by Wang et al. \cite{3} and Jo \cite{4} have modeled bus bunching as a state-transition problem, utilizing GTFS-RT data to track how localized disruptions propagate spatially across urban grids. Olvera-Toscano et al. \cite{10} demonstrated that implementing holding times based on quasi-regular headways can reduce bunching penalties by up to 45\%, provided that the underlying detection mechanism is accurate.

\subsection{GTFS-RT Data and Ingestion Architectures}
The proliferation of open transit data has enabled large-scale operational analyses. Aemmer et al. \cite{11} proposed methodologies to extract performance metrics from GTFS-RT components to classify systematic versus stochastic delays. However, the sheer volume of AVL data poses significant processing challenges \cite{12}. Traditional row-based relational databases (RDBMS) introduce significant latency during the calculation of sequential window functions (e.g., \texttt{LAG} operations over millions of rows) \cite{13}. To address this, recent studies have advocated for column-oriented, embedded analytical databases. Raasveldt and Mühleisen \cite{14} introduced DuckDB as a highly optimized in-process database capable of executing complex analytical queries without network overhead. The application of such architectures for city-scale transit delay prediction has been validated by Boudabbous et al. \cite{15}, emphasizing the need for multi-resolution feature engineering with minimal latency.

\subsection{Machine Learning for Imbalanced Transit Data}
Predicting bus bunching is inherently an imbalanced classification problem, as bunching events constitute a minority class (typically 5\% to 10\% of total observations) in nominal transit operations \cite{16}. In our raw pre-filtered longitudinal corpus, the deterioration class density is below 8\%; this value refers to the full stream before applying any transition-state conditioning. Standard threshold-based classifiers or models optimized for global accuracy fail to capture the minority class, leading to severe under-prediction of anomalies. Chen and Cheng \cite{17} demonstrated that utilizing imbalanced machine learning techniques---specifically focusing on the F1-Score and Precision-Recall Area Under the Curve (PR-AUC)---is mandatory to avoid estimation bias in transport models. Furthermore, Al-Fares et al. \cite{18} proved that handling class imbalance is critical for stochastic transportation anomaly prediction. While deep learning models like the BAT-transformer \cite{19} have shown high accuracy in arrival time prediction, they act as ``black boxes'' and demand high computational resources. In contrast, optimized logistic regression models provide the interpretability required by transit dispatchers while maintaining competitive predictive power if the spatio-temporal features are correctly engineered \cite{20}. Yang et al. \cite{21} provided a comprehensive overview of solutions, noting that while deep learning is popular, linear models with robust feature spaces are often more practical for real-time deployment.

\subsection{Digital Twin Architectures and Edge Computing}
A transit Digital Twin integrates real-time telemetry with predictive models to create a virtual replica of the physical fleet \cite{22,23}. Manandhar et al. \cite{24} outlined the structural requirements for sustainable public transportation DTs, highlighting the necessity for simulation-based ``what-if'' capabilities. However, these capabilities depend entirely on the low-latency generation of EWS. Al-Azzawi et al. \cite{25} proposed DT architectures for Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS) that demand strict computational efficiency to enable continuous synchronization between the physical and virtual states. Consequently, edge-computing paradigms have been identified as a vital enabler for low-latency DTs \cite{26}. By processing data close to the source or utilizing highly efficient in-process analytical tools, transit agencies can circumvent the bottlenecks of centralized cloud architectures \cite{27}.

\section{System Architecture and Methodology}

\subsection{Digital Twin Data Pipeline}
The proposed EWS framework is designed as the predictive layer of a Transit Digital Twin. The pipeline consists of three sequential stages: (1) Ingestion, (2) Transformation, and (3) Inference.

To achieve sub-millisecond latency, we bypass traditional database servers and utilize DuckDB \cite{14}. The architectural decision to embed DuckDB as the primary analytical engine represents a fundamental departure from conventional transit data pipelines. Unlike row-oriented Relational Database Management Systems (RDBMS) such as PostgreSQL, which employ a tuple-at-a-time execution model that incurs significant CPU interpretation overhead and cache misses, DuckDB utilizes a vectorized execution engine. This engine processes data in compressed columnar chunks, maximizing CPU cache locality and allowing for Single Instruction, Multiple Data (SIMD) optimizations. Such architectural characteristics are exceptionally suited for the highly structured nature of GTFS-RT Protocol Buffer (protobuf) payloads, where sequential window operations (e.g., \texttt{LAG} functions over timestamps and delays) dominate the computational workload.

Furthermore, compared to prevalent in-memory frameworks like Pandas, which are severely bottlenecked by single-threaded execution and excessive memory overhead during object instantiation, DuckDB executes complex spatio-temporal joins and state aggregations out-of-core and in parallel. By directly compiling query plans against the columnar representation of the transit telemetry streams, we circumvent the costly serialization-deserialization boundaries inherent in client-server RDBMS paradigms. This synergistic integration of vectorized execution and embedded columnar storage is explicitly responsible for driving the pipeline's inference latency down to the unprecedented \SI{0.00042}{\ms} per record threshold, effectively eliminating the persistence and transformation layer as a computational bottleneck.

Crucially, following the ingestion of the GTFS-RT feed (VehiclePositions and TripUpdates) into this columnar format, the transformation stage includes a strict deduplication protocol. Raw AVL data often contains multiple position updates for a single vehicle while dwelling at a stop. Failure to filter these redundant snapshots results in severe spatial data leakage, where a predictive model correlates a vehicle's state with a previous snapshot of itself at the exact same location, artificially inflating accuracy metrics. The pipeline ensures that only the final departure timestamp for a unique \texttt{trip\_id} and \texttt{stop\_sequence} combination is recorded.

\subsection{Mathematical Formulation of System States}
Let $T_{obs}(i, v_k)$ and $T_{sch}(i, v_k)$ represent the observed and scheduled arrival times, respectively, for vehicle $v_k$ at stop $i$. The delay drift $D$ for a given vehicle is simply the deviation from the schedule:
\begin{equation}
	D(i, v_k) = T_{obs}(i, v_k) - T_{sch}(i, v_k)
\end{equation}

While $D$ measures schedule adherence, system stability is governed by the headway $H$. We define the observed headway $h_{obs}$ between vehicle $v_2$ and its preceding vehicle $v_1$ operating on the same route as:
\begin{equation}
	h_{obs}(i) = T_{obs}(i, v_2) - T_{obs}(i, v_1)
\end{equation}
Similarly, the scheduled headway is:
\begin{equation}
	h_{sch}(i) = T_{sch}(i, v_2) - T_{sch}(i, v_1)
\end{equation}

A bus bunching event ($B$) is defined as a binary state. Following industry standards \cite{1, 10}, a collapse is declared if the observed headway is less than 25\% of the scheduled headway:
\begin{equation}
	B_i =
	\begin{cases}
		1, & \text{if } h_{obs}(i) < 0.25 \cdot h_{sch}(i) \\
		0, & \text{otherwise}
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Spatio-Temporal Feature Engineering ($n-3$ Window)}
To predict the state $B_n$ at the upcoming stop $n$, we extract the historical trajectory of the vehicle over the preceding stops ($n-1, n-2, n-3$). The feature vector $X \in \mathbb{R}^{12}$ captures both the absolute state and the dynamic rate of change (first-order discrete derivatives):
\begin{equation}
	\Delta D_j = D(n-j) - D(n-j-1) \quad \text{for } j \in \{1, 2, 3\}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
	\Delta H_j = h_{obs}(n-j) - h_{obs}(n-j-1) \quad \text{for } j \in \{1, 2, 3\}
\end{equation}

The complete feature vector evaluated at inference time is:
\begin{equation}
	X_n = \left[ D_{n-1}, D_{n-2}, D_{n-3}, h_{n-1}, h_{n-2}, h_{n-3}, \Delta D_{1:3}, \Delta H_{1:3} \right]
\end{equation}

\subsection{Transition State Filter and Persistence Bias Elimination}
A fundamental methodological flaw in existing transit predictive literature is the failure to account for physical inertia (persistence bias). If a vehicle is already bunched at stop $n-1$, predicting that it will remain bunched at stop $n$ is a trivial extrapolation of Newtonian kinematics, not an early warning signal.

To guarantee operational utility, our EWS model is strictly formulated as a Transition State Predictor. We filter the training and evaluation datasets such that the model only observes instances where the vehicle was in a nominal state at the previous stop ($B_{n-1} = 0$). The probability of transitioning into a bunching state at stop $n$ is modeled using a Logistic Regression classifier:
\begin{equation}
	P(B_n=1 \mid B_{n-1}=0, X_n) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(\theta^T X_n + \theta_0)}}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Optimization and Regularization}
Given the severe class imbalance (the transition $0 \rightarrow 1$ occurs in less than 8\% of the nominal observations), optimizing for standard cross-entropy loss often results in a trivial majority-class classifier (predicting all 0s). We apply class weighting inversely proportional to class frequencies to the Log-Loss function, coupled with an L2 regularization term to prevent overfitting to specific corridor bottlenecks:
\begin{equation}
	\mathcal{L}(\theta) = - \sum_{m=1}^{M} w_m \left[ y_m \log(\hat{y}_m) + (1-y_m)\log(1-\hat{y}_m) \right] + \lambda ||\theta||_2^2
\end{equation}
where $w_m$ is the class weight for sample $m$, $y_m \in \{0, 1\}$ is the actual transition state, $\hat{y}_m$ is the predicted probability, and $\lambda$ is the L2 penalty hyperparameter determined via grid search. The decision threshold $\tau$ is not fixed at 0.5; instead, it is dynamically selected to maximize the F1-Score on the validation set.

\subsection{Conformal Prediction for Operational Uncertainty Control}
Point predictions alone are insufficient for high-stakes dispatch decisions because operators need calibrated confidence, not only binary alarms. We therefore wrap the transition classifier with split conformal prediction, using a held-out calibration set to compute nonconformity scores and convert each probabilistic output into a prediction set with finite-sample validity.

Let $s(x)=1-\hat{p}(x)$ be the nonconformity score for the positive class, where $\hat{p}(x)=P(B_n=1\mid B_{n-1}=0, X_n)$. For target miscoverage $\alpha\in(0,1)$ and calibration set of size $N_{cal}$, the quantile threshold is
\begin{equation}
	q_{1-\alpha}=\text{Quantile}_{\lceil (N_{cal}+1)(1-\alpha)\rceil /N_{cal}}\left(\{s_i\}_{i=1}^{N_{cal}}\right).
\end{equation}
The conformal prediction set for a new observation $x$ is then
\begin{equation}
	\Gamma_{\alpha}(x)=\{1\ \text{if}\ s(x)\le q_{1-\alpha};\ 0\ \text{if}\ 1-s(x)\le q_{1-\alpha}\}.
\end{equation}
This mechanism turns the EWS into an uncertainty-aware decision layer: singleton sets trigger high-confidence actions, while ambiguous sets explicitly flag low-confidence cases for conservative control.

\section{Experimental Setup}

\subsection{Dataset Description}
The empirical validation of the proposed framework relies on a massive dataset obtained from the 511.org open data API, capturing the entirety of the San Francisco Municipal Railway (SF Muni) operations for the month of February 2026 \cite{28}. The initial raw dataset contained over 1,000,000 GTFS-RT AVL updates.

Following the strict deduplication protocol described in Section III.A, the dataset was reduced to 205,584 valid, unique stop-level observations. We selected three primary corridors for our experiments, representing high-frequency, mixed-traffic urban environments:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Route 14 (Mission St):} The primary training and temporal validation corridor, characterized by dense commercial zoning and high exogenous traffic noise.
	\item \textbf{Route 38 (Geary Blvd):} An independent arterial corridor used for spatial cross-validation.
	\item \textbf{Route 49 (Van Ness Ave):} A highly congested north-south corridor, also utilized for spatial cross-validation.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Temporal Isolation and Spatial Cross-Validation}
To prevent temporal data leakage (models observing future traffic patterns to predict past events), the dataset was strictly partitioned chronologically. For the baseline model and the primary predictive training on Route 14, data from February 1 to February 21 constituted the training set, while data from February 22 to February 28 served as the hold-out test set.

For spatial cross-validation, the model trained \textit{exclusively} on Route 14 (up to Feb 21) was deployed to infer transitions on Routes 38 and 49 without any retraining or weight adjustment.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
Because the dataset is heavily skewed towards the nominal class, Accuracy is a deceptive metric. We evaluate the models using Precision, Recall (True Positive Rate), the harmonic mean F1-Score, and the Precision-Recall Area Under the Curve (PR-AUC) \cite{17}.

\section{Results}

\subsection{Baseline Analysis (Single-Stop Threshold)}
To justify the necessity of the complex sequential $n-3$ window, we first established a naïve baseline based on conventional thresholding. The baseline model triggers an EWS if the delay drift at the previous stop indicates a sudden spike: $\Delta D_{n-1} > 60$ seconds.

The baseline model exhibited a catastrophic False Positive Rate (FPR) of 38.67\%. Out of 113,697 predicted bunching events, 95,951 were false alarms. This high FPR mathematically proves that isolated delay increments are predominantly caused by transient urban noise (e.g., a long red light cycle) that the transit vehicle often recovers from organically. Relying on a single-stop signal ($n-1$) results in severe alarm fatigue, rendering the EWS useless for a Digital Twin operator.

\subsection{Predictive Performance of the Sequential Framework}
Implementing the Transition State Filter and the $n-3$ spatio-temporal feature vector, the L2-regularized Logistic Regression model was evaluated on the temporal hold-out set of Route 14. Out of 11,811 nominal-state observations in the final week, 390 actual collapse transitions occurred.

The sequential model achieved an F1-Score of 0.8234 ($\sigma=0.0109$, 95\% CI: $[0.8018, 0.8448]$). The precision reached 0.9521 ($\sigma=0.0109$, 95\% CI: $[0.9282, 0.9692]$), meaning that when the EWS alerts the DT operator of an imminent collapse, the system is correct 95\% of the time, effectively eliminating the false-alarm fatigue seen in the baseline. The recall stood at 0.7241, successfully anticipating nearly three-quarters of all bunching events before they manifested.

To further substantiate the statistical rigor of these metrics, a binomial bootstrap analysis ($B=10,000$ iterations) was conducted on the $n=390$ discrete collapse transitions observed during the temporal hold-out period. The resulting variance for both the F1-Score and Precision estimators converged to $\sigma^2 \approx 0.000120$. This narrow dispersion confirms that the sample size is sufficiently robust to yield statistically significant performance bounds, mitigating the risk of Type I and Type II inferential errors within the mixed-traffic operational domain.

\subsection{Conformal Coverage Evaluation}
To validate uncertainty calibration under operational telemetry variability, we evaluated split conformal prediction at a nominal coverage target of 90\%. Empirical coverage remained aligned with the target across missing-telemetry regimes: 91.2\% for $k=0$ (no telemetry drop) and 89.4\% for $k=1$ (single-cycle drop). In parallel, conformal set sizes adapted to uncertainty, expanding from an average of 1.05 labels in nominal conditions to 1.87 labels during telemetry drops. This behavior is consistent with the intended risk-aware dispatch design: calibrated coverage is preserved while ambiguity is made explicit when data quality degrades.

\subsection{Ablation Study of Sequential Window Depth}
To isolate the effect of temporal depth in the sequential encoder, we evaluated five lag configurations while keeping the classifier family and optimization protocol fixed.

