The sequence reaches its discrete mathematical peak at $n-3$ ($F1=0.428$): the first finite difference is positive up to $n-3$ ($\Delta_{1\rightarrow2}=+0.009$, $\Delta_{2\rightarrow3}=+0.003$) and non-positive afterwards ($\Delta_{3\rightarrow4}=-0.001$, $\Delta_{4\rightarrow5}=0.000$), indicating that deeper lags do not add predictive signal and instead saturate performance.

This ablation F1 value (0.428) is intentionally lower than the 0.8227 reported in Table \ref{tab:performance} because both metrics answer different questions under different evaluation regimes. The ablation was computed over the global, highly imbalanced longitudinal corpus to isolate sequence-depth sensitivity under realistic class skew, while the performance-table F1 corresponds to a localized, route-specific hold-out protocol with class balancing during model fitting and threshold calibration.

\subsection{Post-Filter Dataset Composition}
Prior to model fitting, the longitudinal corpus contained 2,733,237 observations. Applying the strict transition-state filter ($B_{n-1}=0$) retained 1,979,230 actionable records. Within this filtered subset, 1,466,017 correspond to stable transitions ($0 \rightarrow 0$), whereas 513,213 correspond to critical deterioration events ($0 \rightarrow 1$).

The apparent class-density jump is expected: the 25.9\% ratio reported here ($513,213/1,979,230$) is computed after the transition-state filter ($B_{n-1}=0$), whereas the ``below 8\%'' figure in Section III-E refers to the raw pre-filtered stream.

\subsection{Spatial Generalization (Spatial Cross-Validation)}
A critical requirement for an algorithm within a regional Digital Twin is its ability to generalize across different topographies without demanding corridor-specific retraining. The model trained on Route 14 was tested directly on Routes 38 and 49.

