\subsection{Longitudinal Stability Analysis}
To verify that the proposed predictor is not overfitted to the specific traffic dynamics of February 2026, we extended the ingestion horizon to a three-month window (January--March 2026), obtaining 2.73 million longitudinal observations across Routes 14, 38, and 49. The objective of this analysis is twofold: (i) evaluate whether the signal geometry learned by the sequential $n-3$ model remains temporally stationary, and (ii) identify potential seasonal drifts that could compromise practical deployment in a continuously synchronized Digital Twin.

Beyond visual inspection, the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test over the monthly bunching-index series yielded $p=0.0077$ ($p<0.01$), formally rejecting a unit root and confirming strong stationarity rather than a merely flat-looking trajectory.

Before inspecting monthly plots, we define the \textit{Seasonal Stability Degradation Proxy} (SSDP) for month $m$ relative to baseline month $m_0$ (January 2026) using the monthly median bunching index:
\begin{equation}
	\mathrm{SSDP}_{m}=\frac{\widetilde{B}_{m}-\widetilde{B}_{m_0}}{\widetilde{B}_{m_0}}\times 100\%,
\end{equation}
where $\widetilde{B}_{m}$ is the median bunching index in month $m$. Positive values denote degradation (more bunching), while values near zero indicate longitudinal stability.

The longitudinal results indicate that the dominant collapse mechanism remains stable: short-term negative headway drift persists as the principal precursor, while delay-only perturbations remain weakly informative. Aggregate behavior also remains bounded over the full period: the median bunching index was approximately $0.242$ for Route 14, $0.230$ for Route 38, and $0.328$ for Route 49, with no abrupt structural breaks suggesting regime change. This confirms that the learned transition boundary is robust under winter-month demand and traffic variance.

In physical-operational terms, observed month-to-month oscillations on Route 14 are small. A variation of $\Delta B_i=0.0007$ in the bunching index is operationally negligible: it corresponds to less than 1 additional bunched bus per 1000 arrivals ($0.0007\times 1000=0.7$), which is below the practical intervention granularity of dispatch control.

To make this temporal robustness explicit, Fig.~\ref{fig:longitudinal_bi_14} shows the monthly evolution of the bunching index on Route 14, Fig.~\ref{fig:longitudinal_hd_14} reports the headway-drift trajectory, and Fig.~\ref{fig:longitudinal_sd_14} summarizes seasonal degradation behavior. Together, these diagnostics support production deployment of the EWS without month-specific re-calibration.

