\subsection{Feature Importance and the Physics of Collapse}
An analysis of the optimal weight vector $\theta$ extracted from the logistic regression reveals a distinct hierarchy of EWS signals.

The most potent predictor of an impending bunching event is the rate of headway collapse at the immediate preceding stop ($\Delta H_{n-1}$), which registered a normalized weight of $w \approx -0.036$. This was followed closely by the absolute observed headway state ($h_{n-1}$) with $w \approx -0.022$.

Conversely, the coefficients for pure delay metrics ($D_{n-1}$ and $\Delta D_{1}$) were an order of magnitude smaller (e.g., $w \approx -0.001$). This provides conclusive empirical backing to Daganzo's theoretical framework \cite{1}: a bus running 5 minutes late (high delay) is operationally safe as long as the bus behind it is also 5 minutes late (stable headway). The system collapses solely when the relative distance derivative turns sharply negative.

\subsection{Computational Benchmark for Edge Deployment}
To validate the architectural viability of the proposal, an inference latency benchmark was conducted on standard consumer hardware (representing an Edge node within a DT). The end-to-end inference process---comprising the DuckDB \texttt{LAG} query for feature extraction and the logistic function evaluation---clocked an average execution time of \SI{0.00042}{\ms} per record.

This latency translates to a throughput capacity of over 2.38 million AVL events per second on a single CPU core. Such extreme computational efficiency confirms that the proposed EWS framework can easily scale to ingest simultaneous GTFS-RT feeds from multiple metropolitan transit agencies without requiring heavy cloud-compute clusters, aligning with the low-latency Edge-Cloud paradigms described by He et al. \cite{26}.

\subsubsection{Benchmark Contextualization}
To contextualize this latency against common analytics backends used in transit operations, Table \ref{tab:benchmark_context} compares representative per-record inference times. Relative to the Postgres baseline, the embedded DuckDB execution path yielded an observed acceleration of approximately 45x in this study.

