\section{Discussion and Future Work}

\subsection{Operational Lead Time}
The generation of an EWS is only valuable if it provides human operators or automated control loops sufficient time to execute mitigating actions. By predicting the collapse at stop $n$ using data up to stop $n-1$, our model guarantees a minimum Lead Time of 1 stop (typically 2 to 4 minutes in dense urban environments). Because the latency of the algorithm is virtually zero, this entire temporal window is preserved for intervention strategies, such as dynamic holding (instructing the leading bus to dwell longer at the platform) or stop-skipping (instructing the trailing bus to express past minor stops) \cite{10}.

\subsection{Limitations in Mixed-Traffic Environments}
While the $n-3$ window effectively filters out significant portions of urban noise, the validation was inherently conducted in mixed-traffic corridors (SF Muni). In these environments, exogenous factors outside the control of the transit agency---such as vehicular congestion, illegal parking in bus stops, and unpredictable traffic signal delays---introduce a baseline level of stochastic variance that limits the theoretical maximum of the recall metric (currently capped at $\approx 0.77$).

\subsection{Resilience and API Limitations}
The operational deployment of the proposed Digital Twin pipeline is fundamentally constrained by the rate limits of the external telemetry provider. The 511.org open data API enforces a strict quota of 60 requests per hour. Because a complete state update requires two distinct endpoints (\texttt{VehiclePositions} and \texttt{TripUpdates}), the system is limited to 30 complete cycles per hour, establishing a theoretical minimum polling interval of 120 seconds. To buffer against transient network latency and prevent connection throttling, our ingestion engine operates on a 130-second polling cycle ($T_{poll} = 130$ s).

This discrete, low-frequency sampling introduces a stochastic quantization error into the continuous-time physical system. Let $p_{loss}$ denote the probability of a packet drop or API timeout during a polling cycle. The uncertainty in the observed arrival time $T_{obs}$ grows proportionally with consecutive missed updates. If $k$ consecutive cycles are missed, the bounded error in the delay drift $D$ and the observed headway $h_{obs}$ can be modeled as $\epsilon \sim \mathcal{U}(0, k \cdot T_{poll})$. The cascading effect of this uncertainty on the bunching index ($B_i$) and the headway deviation ($\Delta H$) poses a severe risk of generating false EWS alerts.

To preserve the resilience of the classification model, the pipeline implements a deterministic flagging and imputation protocol. When $k=1$, missing spatial coordinates are approximated using linear interpolation based on the GTFS shape geometry and the last known velocity vector. The corresponding $D$ and $h_{obs}$ are re-calculated with an appended uncertainty flag. However, if $k \ge 2$ ($> 260$ s of missing telemetry), interpolation is deemed physically invalid due to the high variance of urban traffic. In such cases, the observation is flagged as \textit{stale}, and the corresponding $(n-3)$ sequential feature window $X_n$ is explicitly dropped from the inference queue. This fail-safe mechanism ensures that the predictive model is only fed high-fidelity data, deliberately trading a momentary loss in system recall for the preservation of the 0.95 precision.

\subsection{Transition to Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) Systems}
Future work will focus on calibrating and deploying the proposed EWS framework within Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) systems featuring physically segregated, exclusive lanes. Recent literature demonstrates that applying dynamic holding control strategies in segregated BRT corridors can reduce bunching penalties significantly \cite{10, 29}.

By migrating this algorithmic framework to a BRT Digital Twin, the exogenous traffic variance is mathematically isolated. The primary drivers of $\Delta H$ become strictly endogenous: passenger boarding rates (dwell times) and individual driver behavior. We hypothesize that applying this exact sequential model in an exclusive-lane topology will drive the F1-Score above 0.90, providing an impeccably clean signal \cite{30} to trigger automated, closed-loop holding controls \cite{10} without requiring human-in-the-loop validation.

\section{Conclusion}
This paper studies bus bunching prediction in mixed-traffic transit environments using a sequential Digital Twin framework. We find that a multi-stop ($n-3$) spatio-temporal window, optimized via L2-regularized Logistic Regression, effectively filters urban noise, achieving a transition prediction precision of 0.95 (95\% CI: [0.93, 0.97]) and a corrected F1-Score of 0.8234 (95\% CI: [0.80, 0.84]). The evidence is consistent with the hypothesis that the rate of headway collapse ($\Delta H$) is the singular dominant precursor to systemic degradation, though stochastic exogenous variance in mixed-traffic corridors limits inference about absolute anomaly prediction. These findings inform proactive transit management and Edge-Cloud monitoring by providing computationally efficient (sub-millisecond) early warning signals.

\section*{Reproducibility}
To ensure methodological transparency and support further research, the full DuckDB ingestion scripts, transformation pipelines, and hyperparameter configuration matrices utilized in this study are open-source and available at: \url{https://github.com/gentleman-programming/pp-pipe-dt}.

